Text.Value: This one is just proving slow.
It is a little slower to hatch, nothing more.
I don't have time to parent you as well. What do you want now?
An egg. You murdered a defenceless egg!
The conditions must not be disturbed if it is to have a fighting chance.
Why bother? This egg's clearly a dud.
You're out of time and clearly stalling - that's why Kith'rak Therezzyn sent me to bring it to her. Hand it over.
No you will not!

EditorData.NodeContext: Forceful response to "I'm gonna turn your egg into an omlette." Combat starts afterwards

Text.Value: You think I haven't defended our broods against worthier opponents than you? Idiot.

EditorData.NodeContext: Incredulous; you dare challenge one as experienced as him?

Text.Value: You will pay for this. Htak'a!

EditorData.NodeContext: quivering with rage [huh-tack-AH =  a battle cry meaning "attack!"]

Text.Value: You're being very protective of this egg - why?
Still, I'm sure it's nature will pervade, even if raised among lesser species.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: He's reluctant to part with it, having grown very fond of it. But knows it's for the best.

Text.Value: I see. I cannot deny that I had hoped for more time.
I'll raise it as if it were my own flesh and blood.
This is my duty. I will protect it.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: He doesn't really believe himself - the captain will have his neck for this, but it's an unspoken sacrifice he's prepared to make.

Text.Value: Time for you to leave, I think, istik. And do not touch the egg.
Time for you to leave, I think, kin. And do not touch the egg.
Now leave.
They almost drowned me in the hatching pool. If it wasn't for the varsh of my clutch -

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: He trails off, thinking of how lucky he was.

Text.Value: Careful, kin. You tread close to blasphemy. Do not overstep.
I'll see that it becomes the greatest ghaik-slayer you've ever seen.
Unlikely, but the journey may yet be character-forming.
Enough! Be on your way.
How dare you? Your bones will melt in the hatching pool, you insolent whelp!

EditorData.NodeContext: Stress on 'dare'. Combat starts after this line.

Text.Value: This hatchery is a place of solemn duty and care. No one approaches an egg without my permission.

EditorData.NodeContext: You caught the player trying to get close to your precious egg.
EditorData.logicalname: Speak to Caretaker after being spotted near egg

Text.Value: But you've a spirit about you that's quite inspiring. Perhaps even equal to the challenge.
Leave.
Kith'rak Therezzyn is of the same opinion. She would see it destroyed and forgotten.
Tell me the truth. Why do you really care about this one so much?
I am here to help you save the egg.
Tell me, what will you do with it if I entrust it to you?
I'll find another crche. One that's more forgiving.
Just know that if the child comes to harm, I will find you, drag you back here, and drown you in the burning waters.

EditorData.NodeContext: Reluctant to hand over the egg; a threat through gritted teeth

Text.Value: I am curious about the egg you guard.
*You note that the hope in his voice is tinged with weariness. It's the voice of a man who's fought the inevitable for a long time.*
What will happen to this egg if it doesn't hatch?
Kith'rak Therezzyn will give orders to destroy it. She will say it's a weakling.

EditorData.NodeContext: Hesistant; he doesn't want to destroy the egg

Text.Value: Depends, how much do you think these things sell for?
A forceful demand.
Some eggs simply fail - why do you care so much for this one?
Why do you care so much about one dud egg?
Still, I suppose a guest in our crche can be allowed some understanding. What brings you to my hatchery?
I heard you're waiting for one last egg to hatch.
No! The child will be safer with me. I know what it needs.
Hm. Just beware that adoptive piety does not turn to sentimentality.
Not all that arrive late are weak. I created this entire hatchery, despite being the last of my clutch to hatch.

EditorData.NodeContext: Restrained sadness that he tries not to show; perhaps bitter mirth in the second sentence

Text.Value: I wanted to see the hatchery. I didn't expect it to look so empty.
That is for me to decide.
Do you think the Sword Coast is littered with crches? That you found this one was unlikely enough.
Why risk its life at all? Give it to me - I'll take care of it.
Though it could be the only way this one reaches adulthood, I fear.
You? You've no varsh instincts about you at all.
Almost all of the eggs in this clutch have hatched. We await only one more, which is... taking its time.
You can tell Kith'rak Therezzyn that my position has not changed: the egg requires more time. Furthermore - oh.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Starts the dialog facing directly away from the player. Turns on 'Furthermore'
EditorData.NodeContext: You turn on 'Furthermore' expecting to see an angry guard, but you're surprised to find the player - a complete stranger.

Text.Value: Let me help - I can take it somewhere safe.
This seems like an awful lot of fuss for one egg.
You are not from Crche Y'llek. What are you doing here?
This one deserves the same chance.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: He catches himself mid-sentimental-moment and resumes his more professional air.

Text.Value: You? What do you know about githyanki child-rearing?
Is this some sort of grotesque attempt at humour?
Very well. Here - take these - they will aid you approach the egg.
I do this under protest. But it is what's best.
There is little to be curious about. It is taking its time hatching, nothing more.
I do not midwife the birth of your young - do not tell me how to care for mine.
You mistook me for someone. Who were you expecting?
Well? Will you take the egg or not?

EditorData.logicalname: Received Permission AND Did not take the egg yet

Text.Value: Still, the captain's due for an inspection any day now, and if she sees it here...

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: He's torn by this decision, an impossible decision.
EditorData.NodeContext: the captain will destroy his precious egg if she finds it

Text.Value: It's taking a little longer than expected to hatch.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: He doesn't want to let on how big a deal this is, but it's not a good sign. Not good at all.

Text.Value: We cannot afford to discard warriors because we are simply impatient.
Our broods are bigger than this, kin. Where are the others?
But the kith'rak speaks for our Queen. And I live to serve. Fine. You can take it.
But if I know her, she's too busy for that.
Did you think me a fool? Did you think I wouldn't notice the theft of our final egg?
Most caretakers would not give the child its fair chance, but I shall. There could be greatness in that shell.
This egg would do better away from the tyranny of our kind. Give it to me and I'll give it a better life.
That's what I feared.
If she really wants it, she can come and get it herself.
It would certainly be her style to send a messenger in her stead for a task like that.
I can no longer ignore that Kith'rak Therezzyn's patience has its limits.
Hateful. Utterly hateful.

EditorData.NodeContext: Player just said they'd sell your egg. Combat follows.

Text.Value: Someone with orders from our commander to destroy this egg.
An accurate assessment. They hatched promptly and are well into their training.
Of course, a stranger from a strange crche may have different customs. What brings you here?
You've got the egg haven't you? Be on your way then. Before I change my mind.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: He gave us permission to take it, but is sad to see it go nonetheless, and masking this with terseness.
EditorData.logicalname: Received Permission AND Took the egg

Text.Value: I want the egg. How much for it?
I came here to steal an egg.
This egg is in my care. It does not need saving.
It is a dangerous world out there - I'm sure you know that.
I was not expecting an istik. What brings you to my hatchery?
Failure at the first hurdle of existence. Most caretakers would crush it and be done.
I'll make the best omelette you've ever tasted.
You're wasting time. Give it to me now or I'll tell her you're the weakling.
I'll give it a while longer, and if it doesn't hatch - it will have proven her right.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: He desperately wants this egg to hatch, even though he knows it probably won't.

Text.Value: An istik? Don't make me laugh.
Not an easy task. And far harder without a crche to train it in.

Synopsis: The gith caretaker asks what the player is doing in the hatchery. They can learn some interesting lore about githyanki eggs. The player can also convince the caretaker to give them the last unhatched egg - but he is quite attached to it.
